{{About|the accent|the shoe|Brogue shoe|video game|Brogue (video game)}} {{Wiktionary|brogue}} The term '''brogue''' ({{IPAc-en|b|r|əʊ|ɡ}} {{respell|BROHG}}) generally refers to an [[Hiberno-English|Irish accent]]. Less commonly, it may also refer to certain other regional forms of English, in particular those of [[Scottish English|Scotland]] or the English [[West Country dialects|West Country]].<ref>''brogue'', noun. Cambridge Dictionaries Online.</ref><ref>McArthur, Tom and Roshan (2005). ''Concise Oxford Companion to the English Language''. OUP Oxford. {{ISBN|978-0192806376}}</ref>
The word was first recorded in 1689.<ref>McCrum, Robert et al. (1986). ''The Story of English''. Viking Press. {{ISBN|978-0670804672}}</ref> Multiple [[Etymology|etymologies]] have been proposed: it may derive from the [[Irish language|Irish]] ''bróg'' ("shoe"), the [[Brogue shoe|type of shoe]] traditionally worn by the people of Ireland and the [[Scottish Highlands]], and hence possibly originally meant "the speech of those who call a shoe a 'brogue'".<ref>[http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=brogue&allowed_in_frame=0 brogue], Online Etymology Dictionary</ref> It is also possible that the term comes from the [[Irish language|Irish]] word ''barróg'', meaning "a hold (on the tongue)", thus "accent" or "speech impediment".<ref>{{cite web|title=brogue|url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/cgi-bin/mwwodarch.pl?Jul.10.2009|work=Merriam-Webster Online|publisher=Merriam-Webster, Incorporated|accessdate=19 July 2012|author=Merriam-Webster Online|year=2012}}</ref> A famous [[false etymology]] states that the word stems from the supposed perception that the Irish spoke English so peculiarly that it was as if they did so "with a shoe in their mouths".<ref>Walshe, Shane et al. (2009). ''Irish English As Represented in Film''. Peter Lang Pub Inc. p. 4. {{ISBN|978-3631586822}}</ref>
