A '''denied area''' is an [[espionage|intelligence]] [[term of art]] describing an extremely hostile operational environment with heavy surveillance.<ref name="Redmond">{{cite book |last=Redmond |first=Paul J. |author-link= |year=2010 |chapter=The Challenges of Counterintelligence |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=X7i_I_np11IC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA545#v=onepage&q&f=false |editor-last=Johnson |editor-first=Loch K. |editor1-link=Loch K. Johnson |title=The Oxford Handbook of National Security Intelligence |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=X7i_I_np11IC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false |location=New York |publisher=Oxford University Press, Inc. |page=545 |isbn=9780199704699}}</ref>
The [[United States Department of Defense]] defines a denied area as ''"an area under enemy or unfriendly control in which friendly forces cannot expect to operate successfully within existing operational constraints and force capabilities."''{{citation needed|date=April 2015}}
When a reference is made to a friendly force denying an area to the enemy, such as a reference to friendly forces employing area-denial weapons, the intent is to create an area in which the enemy cannot operate without extreme risk.
[[Land mine]]s can be used as area-denial weapons, and some modern semi-autonomous or remotely controlled [[artillery]] units can serve this purpose as well. In theory, [[nuclear weapon|nuclear]], [[biological weapon|biological]], and [[chemical weapon|chemical]] [[weapons]] can also serve this purpose, for varying lengths of times, though such weapons have not yet been used for this purpose in major [[war]]s, although such weapons have been used for other purposes.
Some effective tactics for creating a denied area do not require a significant continuing commitment of personnel or additional material. For example, once a minefield is in place, no upkeep is required unless a significant percentage of the mines have been detonated or destroyed—no residual force commitment is required. This is why a denied area may well exist behind enemy lines when, if it were secured by friendly forces on the ground, it might be considered a forward position. When hostilities end, these areas can be very dangerous and expensive to clean up, assuming that one of the combatants is willing to. (see [[UXO]], [[bomb disposal]], [[land mine]], and the contamination concerns for [[weapon of mass destruction|unconventional weapons]]).
A [[dirty bomb]] is a potential option for an area denial weapon that might be more accessible to small [[paramilitary]] or [[terrorist groups]].
==See also== *[[Area denial weapons]] *[[Scorched earth]]
