{{Infobox book | name = Writing and Difference | title_orig = L'écriture et la différence | translator = Alan Bass | image = File:Writing and Difference, French edition.jpg | caption = Cover of the first edition | author = [[Jacques Derrida]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = France | language = French | series = | subject = [[Philosophy]] | publisher = [[Éditions du Seuil]] | release_date = 1967 | english_release_date = 1978 | media_type = Print | pages = 446 (English translation) | isbn = 0-415-25383-7 | dewey= | congress= | oclc= | preceded_by = | followed_by = }} '''''Writing and Difference''''' ({{lang-fr|L'écriture et la différence}}) is a book by French philosopher [[Jacques Derrida]], collecting some of the early lectures and essays that established his international fame. It was published in 1967 alongside ''[[Of Grammatology]]'' and ''[[Speech and Phenomena]]''.
==Summary==
===Cogito and the History of Madness=== {{Main article|Cogito and the History of Madness}}
The collection contains the essay ''Cogito and the History of Madness'', a critique of [[Michel Foucault]]. It was first given as a lecture on March 4, 1963, at a conference at the ''[[Collège philosophique]]'', which Foucault attended, and caused a rift between the two,<ref name="Powell06p34-5">Powell (2006), pp. 34–5{{full citation needed|date=April 2014}}</ref> possibly prompting Foucault to write ''[[The Order of Things]]'' (1966) and ''[[The Archaeology of Knowledge]]'' (1969).<ref name="GinzburgNihilism">Carlo Ginzburg (1976), ''Il formaggio e i vermi'', translated in 1980 as ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=4IUREWq_o3MC The Cheese and the Worms: The Cosmos of a Sixteenth-Century Miller]'', trans. Anne Tedeschi (Baltimore: Johns Hopkins University Press), xviii. {{ISBN|978-0-8018-4387-7}}</ref>
===Violence and Metaphysics=== In "Violence and Metaphysics," Derrida comments on the writings of [[Emmanuel Levinas]]. He honors Levinas for his ethical philosophy of openness to the [[Other (philosophy)|Other]]. Indeed, he goes along with the idea that to live for the Other is the highest good. But he challenges the idea that only [[face-to-face interaction]] can be ethical. Whereas Levinas sees written communication as dead and unresponsive, Derrida argues that writing can be just as valuable a space for ethical encounter. He writes, in characteristic support for writing: "Is it not possible to invert all of Levinas’s statements on this point? By showing, for example, that writing can assist itself, for it has time and freedom, escaping better than speech from empirical urgencies."<ref>''Writing and Difference'', 102</ref>
===The Structuralist Controversy=== Included in the collection is his 1966 lecture at [[Johns Hopkins University]], which changed the course of the conference leading it to be renamed ''The Structuralist Controversy'', and caused Derrida to receive his first major attention outside France. The lecture is titled ''[[Structure, Sign, and Play in the Discourse of the Human Sciences]]''.
